esponse to the biopolitics of the human body, and the breakdowns this has generated. To do this, he investigates how actors in pivotal institutions -the Vatican, the United Nations, U.S. Federal Bioethics-reconceived human dignity as the bearer of intrinsic worth, only to become frustrated by the Sisyphean struggle of turning its conceptions into practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBioethics. 0aHuman rights. 0aRespect for persons. 4aBioethics. 4aCommission on Human Rights. 4aHuman Dignity. 4aPresident's Council on Bioethics. 4aVatican II. 4aanthropology. 4abiopower. 4ahuman rights. 70(DE-588)4006791-90(DE-627)1045852340(DE-576)208867074aBioethik2gnd 70(DE-588)4038654-50(DE-627)1062312190(DE-576)209031360aMenschenwürde2gnd 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267798zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823267798.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK